Continui montes] De Chaup py's de- scription (iii. 284) of the valley of the Licenza is, that it is the only valley which euts the vast range of mountains extending from the Campagna above Tibur to Carseoli, about forty-five miles from Rome. With- out this valley, he says, this immense body would be a continuous mass. The valley is not formed by a simple depression of the mountains, but they seem to open down to their foundations to produce it. This ho thinks gives more force to the word ¹ late- brae ⁷ in v. 15. The valley, he says, seems to have neither entrance nor exit. It lies nearly north and south, which eorre- sponds with the description of the text.
